{{Steels}}
'''Cementite''' (or '''iron carbide''') is a [[Chemical compound|compound]] of [[iron]] and [[carbon]], more precisely an intermediate transition metal [[carbide]] with the formula Fe<sub>3</sub>C. By weight, it is 6.67% carbon and 93.3% iron. It has an [[orthorhombic]] crystal structure.<ref name="smith363">{{harvnb|Smith|Hashemi|2006|p=363}}</ref> It is a hard, brittle material,<ref name="smith363"/> normally classified as a [[ceramic]] in its pure form, and is a frequently found and important constituent in [[ferrous metallurgy]]. While cementite is present in most steels and cast irons,<ref name="Durand">{{harvnb|Durand-Charre|2003}}</ref> it is produced as a raw material in the iron carbide process, which belongs to the family of alternative ironmaking technologies. The name ''cementite'' originated from the research of [[Floris Osmond]] and J. Werth, where the structure of solidified steel consists of a kind of cellular tissue in theory, with [[Allotropes of iron|ferrite]] as the nucleus and Fe<sub>3</sub>C the envelope of the cells. The carbide therefore ''cemented'' the iron.<ref>{{cite journal |author=H. K. D. H. Bhadeshia |year=2020 |title=Cementite |journal=International Materials Reviews |doi=10.1080/09506608.2018.1560984 |volume=65 |issue=1|pages=1–27 |doi-access=free }}</ref>

==Metallurgy==
[[File:Kristallstruktur Zementit.png|thumb|left|Orthorhombic Fe<sub>3</sub>C. Iron atoms are blue.]] 
[[File:Iron carbon phase diagram.svg|thumb|The iron-carbon phase diagram]]

In the iron–carbon system (i.e. [[plain-carbon steel]]s and [[cast iron]]s) it is a common constituent because [[Allotropes of iron|ferrite]] can contain at most 0.02wt% of uncombined carbon.<ref>{{Cite journal|url= https://www.researchgate.net/publication/277605401 |title=Cementite Formation from Hematite–Graphite Mixture by Simultaneous Thermal–Mechanical Activation |journal=Metallurgical and Materials Transactions B |volume=46 |issue=2 |pages=813–823 |doi=10.1007/s11663-014-0228-3 |last1=Ashrafzadeh |first1=Milad |last2=Soleymani |first2=Amir Peyman |last3=Panjepour |first3=Masoud |last4=Shamanian |first4=Morteza |year=2015|s2cid=98253213 }}</ref> Therefore, in carbon steels and cast irons that are slowly cooled, a portion of the carbon is in the form of cementite.<ref>{{harvnb|Smith|Hashemi|2006|pp=366–372}}</ref> Cementite forms directly from the melt in the case of [[cast iron|white cast iron]]. In carbon [[steel]], cementite precipitates from [[austenite]] as austenite transforms to ferrite on slow cooling, or from [[martensite]] during [[tempering (metallurgy)|tempering]]. An intimate mixture with ferrite, the other product of austenite, forms a [[lamellar structure]] called [[pearlite]].

While cementite is thermodynamically unstable, eventually being converted to austenite (low carbon level) and graphite (high carbon level) at higher temperatures, it does not decompose on heating at temperatures below the [[Eutectic system#Eutectoid|eutectoid]] temperature (723&nbsp;°C) on the metastable iron-carbon phase diagram.

==Pure form==
Cementite changes from [[ferromagnetism|ferromagnetic]] to [[paramagnetism|paramagnetic]] at its [[Curie temperature]] of approximately 480 K.<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://zenodo.org/record/1431493 |author=S.W.J. Smith |author2=W. White |author3=S.G. Barker |title=The Magnetic Transition Temperature of Cementite |journal=Proc. Phys. Soc. Lond. |volume=24 |issue=1 |pages=62–69 |year=1911 |doi=10.1088/1478-7814/24/1/310}}</ref>

[[File:Cementite-pV.svg|thumb|Molar volume vs. pressure for cementite at room temperature.]]
A natural iron carbide (containing minor amounts of nickel and cobalt) occurs in [[iron meteorite]]s and is called [[cohenite]] after the German mineralogist [[Emil Cohen]], who first described it.<ref>Vagn F. Buchwald, Handbook of Iron Meteorites, University of California Press 1975</ref> As carbon is one of the possible minor light alloy components of metallic planetary cores, the high-pressure/high-temperature properties of cementite (Fe<sub>3</sub>C) as a simple proxy for cohenite are studied experimentally. The figure shows the compressional behaviour at room temperature.

==Other iron carbides==
There are other forms of [[metastability|metastable]] iron carbides that have been identified in tempered steel and in the industrial [[Fischer-Tropsch process]]. These include '''epsilon (ε) carbide''', [[Hexagonal crystal system|hexagonal close-packed]] Fe<sub>2-3</sub>C, precipitates in plain-carbon steels of carbon content > 0.2%, tempered at 100–200&nbsp;°C. [[Non-stoichiometric compound|Non-stoichiometric]] ε-carbide dissolves above ~200&nbsp;°C, where Hägg carbides and cementite begin to form. '''Hägg carbide''', [[Monoclinic crystal system|monoclinic]] Fe<sub>5</sub>C<sub>2</sub>, precipitates in hardened [[tool steel]]s tempered at 200–300&nbsp;°C.<ref>Gunnar Hägg, ''Z. Krist.'', Vol. 89, p 92-94, 1934.</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Smith |first1=William F. |title=Structure and properties of engineering alloys. |date=1981 |publisher=McGraw-Hill |location=New York |isbn=978-0-07-0585607 |pages=61–62}}</ref> It has also been found naturally as the mineral [[Edscottite]] in the [[Wedderburn meteorite]]<ref>{{Cite web|url =https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/this-meteorite-came-from-the-core-of-another-planet-inside-it-a-new-mineral-20190830-p52mhg.html |title=This meteorite came from the core of another planet. Inside it, a new mineral |last=Mannix |first=Liam |date=2019-08-31 |website=The Age |language=en |access-date=2019-09-14}}</ref> Characterization of different iron carbides is not at all a trivial task, and often X-ray diffraction is complemented by [[Mössbauer spectroscopy]].

